Address Details Geocode Latitude Number

The geographic latitude of a point on the earth is a measurement in degrees north or south of the equator reference to a prescribed datum. Latitudes south of the equator are expressed as a negative number, north of the equator as positive.
Usage Example: -33.91277417
Address Details Geocode Longitude Number

The geographic longitude of a point on the earth is a measurement in degrees east or west of the Greenwich Meridian to a prescribed datum. Longitudes east of Greenwich are expressed as a positive number, west of Greenwich as negative.
Usage Example: -150.91277417
Address Details Geocode Positional Uncertainty Number

Positional uncertainty is the horizontal uncertainty of the coordinates, in meters at the 95% confidence level, with respect to the defined reference frame.
It is intended to be a measure for physical address point features.

Usage Example: 10.000 This is a measure of the closeness of the location of the point in relation to true position on the earth. That is, we are 95% confident that the true position lies within 10 metres of the position given by the geocode.
Address Details Mesh Block Code

This is a code which is defined using 2011 SLA Boundaries, Dwellings, Urban and Rural, Land Use, Cadastre, Gazetted Suburbs and Localities, Topography and Shape. The 11 digits code comprises S/T (State & Territory) identifier (1 digit), Mesh Block identifier (10 digits). Mesh Blocks are the smallest geographic region in the Australian Statistical Geographic Standard (ASGS) and form the basis for the larger regions of the ASGS.
A list of Mesh Block codes can be found at http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/1270.0.55.001July%202011?OpenDocument
Organisation Details Organisation Industry 2006 Code

This is a code which identifies the classification of the industry in which the organisation operated during the relevant period. The Australian and New Zealand Standard Industrial Classification 2006 (ANZSIC) coding system has a 4 level hierarchical structure, where subdivision, group, class and subclass levels are denoted by numeric codes.
A list of ANZSIC 2006 code can be found on http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/1292.02006%20(Revision%201.0)?OpenDocument
Organisation Details Organisation Industry 2006 Description
This is the description of the 2006 Australian and New Zealand Standard Industrial Classification (ANZSIC) code.
A list of ANZSIC 2006 descriptions can be found on http://www.abs.gov.au/AUSSTATS/abs@.nsf/DetailsPage/1292.02006%20(Revision%201.0)?OpenDocument
Organisation Details Organisation Industry 2006 Extended Code

This is a code to identify the main business activity during the relevant period. The industry coding regime is a modified version of the Australian and New Zealand Standard Industrial Classification (ANZSIC), produced jointly by the Australian Bureau of Statistics (ABS) and Statistics New Zealand. The industry code is made up of five digits, where the leading two digits denote the industry division.
Search for "Business Industry Code" on www.ato.gov.au.
